# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: actix-actor-model
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] Actix is a rust library providing a framework for developing concurrent applications.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] Actix is built on the Actor Model which allows applications to be written as a group of independently executing but cooperating "Actors" which communicate via messages.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] Actors are objects which encapsulate state and behavior and run within the *Actor System* provided by the actix library.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] Actors run within a specific execution context `Context<A>`.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] The context object is available only during execution.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] Each actor has a separate execution context.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] The execution context also controls the lifecycle of an actor.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] Actors communicate exclusively by exchanging messages.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] The sending actor can optionally wait for the response.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] Actors are not referenced directly, but by means of addresses.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] Any rust type can be an actor, it only needs to implement the `Actor` trait.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] To be able to handle a specific message the actor has to provide a `Handler<M>` implementation for this message.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] The message can be handled in an asynchronous fashion.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] Actor can spawn other actors or add futures or streams to execution context.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] The `Actor` trait provides several methods that allow controlling the actor's lifecycle.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] An actor always starts in the `Started` state.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] During this state the actor's `started()` method is called.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] The `Actor` trait provides a default implementation for this method.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] The actor context is available during this state and the actor can start more actors or register async streams or do any other required configuration.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] After an Actor's `started()` method is called, the actor transitions to the `Running` state.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] The Actor can stay in `running` state indefinitely.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] An actor can restore from the `stopping` state to the `running` state by creating a new address or adding an event object, and by returning `Running::Continue`.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] If an actor changed state to `stopping` because `Context::stop()` is called then the context immediately stops processing incoming messages and calls `Actor::stopping()`.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] If the actor does not restore back to the `running` state, all unprocessed messages are dropped.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] By default this method returns `Running::Stop` which confirms the stop operation.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] If the actor does not modify the execution context during the stopping state, the actor state changes to `Stopped`.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] This state is considered final and at this point the actor is dropped.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] An Actor communicates with other actors by sending messages.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] A message can be any rust type which implements the `Message` trait.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] `Message::Result` defines the return type.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] Let's define a simple `Ping` message - an actor which will accept this message needs to return `Result<bool, std::io::Error>`.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] How to start an actor depends on its context.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] Spawning a new async actor is achieved via the `start` and `create` methods of the `Actor` trait.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] It provides several different ways of creating actors; for details check the docs.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] Let's take a look at the `Result` type defined for the `impl Handler` in the above example.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] See how we're returning a `Result<bool, std::io::Error>`?
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] We're able to respond to our actor's incoming message with this type because it has the `MessageResponse` trait implemented for that type.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] Sometimes it makes sense to respond to incoming messages with types that don't have this trait implemented for them.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] When that happens we can implement the trait ourselves.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix-actor] Here's an example where we're responding to a `Ping` message with a `GotPing`, and responding with `GotPong` for a `Pong` message.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] Cheng in Santa Clara, California, in 1990.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] Cheng, born in Chiayi in 1945, graduated from the Texas A&M School of Medicine with an M.D./Ph.D. in the 1970s.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] He was briefly employed by Mostek in Massachusetts from 1982 to 1983, switching to nearby Wang Laboratories where he was employed to design a digital PBX system.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] In 1984 he was hired by Lucent Technologies as the lead designer of a fiber-optic communications system, and finally in 1987 he was hired by Digital Equipment Corporation, where he was the program manager of networking.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] Cheng moved from Massachusetts to California to found Actix Systems, combining his disparate experience in the computer industry to specialize in designing graphics adapters.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] The company initially focused on a subset of graphics adapters known as GUI accelerators, which were designed specifically to speed up the drawing of elements in a graphical user interface (GUI) and to enhance its overall visual appearance by increasing the color depth and resolution.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] Actix was one of the first companies to design products in this field.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] Their first product was the Tiger 10, released in August 1991 and aimed at corporate users of Microsoft's Windows 3.0.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] The Tiger 10 shipped with a proprietary device driver for Windows, while the card featured TIGA graphics processors manufactured by Texas Instruments.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] It supported the standard VGA resolution of 640 by 480 pixels, all the way up to 1280-by-960-pixel Super VGA, with certain display modes possessing a 90 MHz refresh rate.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] A month later, the company released the Quantum VGA, a GUI accelerator based on S3 Incorporated's 86C911 chipset.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] The Quantum VGA was received warmly in *InfoWorld*, where reviewer Jim Canning wrote that the board offered "major relief to beleaguered 80286s and 80386SXes".
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] Actix followed up the Quantum VGA with the HiColor Spectra Board, a consumer-oriented, general-purpose graphics adapter based on Tseng Labs' ET 4000 chip that boosted the standard VGA color depth from 256 colors to 32,768, owing to a Sierra RAMDAC on board.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] In January 1992, Actix introduced the first two models in its long line of GraphicsEngine adapters.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] Called the GraphicsEngine VGA, they were also based on S3's GUI accelerator chip and comprised two models: one with 512 KB of video RAM, and another with 1 MB.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] The former supported up to a 1024-by-768-pixel resolution with 4-bit color depth, while the latter supported up to a 1280-by-960-pixel resolution with 8-bit color depth.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] In March 1992, the company introduced the GraphicsEngine Display Accelerator, which incorporated the same RAMDAC as the HiColor Spectra, allowing the board to display 16-bit color at a 1280-by-1024-pixel resolution.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] Both boards received mixed assessments in *PC Magazine*, while *InfoWorld* rated the GraphicsEngine Display Accelerator the fastest board on the low-end of the GUI accelerator market.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] By the end of 1993, Actix had moved to a larger office in Santa Clara, which housed its 20 employees (up from 10 in 1992).
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] The company was described by *Transpacific* magazine as protective of the details of their operations, only divulging that they posted $9 million in sales in 1993.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] The company introduced their first VESA Local Bus product with the GraphicsEngine 32VL in mid-1993.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] The VESA Local Bus was a motherboard technology that allowed expansion cards to access the memory bus of Intel's i486 processor directly, breaking the bottleneck of the antiquated but still commonplace Industry Standard Architecture bus and allowing for much-accelerated graphics output.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] Actix followed up with its first two products based on the Peripheral Component Interconnect (PCI) bus, the GraphicsEngine 64 PCI and GraphicsEngine Ultra 64 PCI, in 1994.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] PCI was an entirely new motherboard bus standard invented by Intel; it had much higher bandwidth than both ISA and VESA Local Bus and eventually came to dominate the motherboard landscape in the mid-1990s.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] One of the company's last products was the GraphicsEngine Ultra AV in 1995.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] Powered by S3's Vision968 graphics chipset and a Texas Instruments RAMDAC, it could display graphics at up to a 1600-by-1200-pixel resolution.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] The company coasted through 1996 with $17 million in annual sales.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] By this point the company had moved again to Sunnyvale, California, and employed 27 workers.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] Actix in 1997 planned a pivot to providing video conferencing products for enterprises.
[src:actix-actor-model/actix] These plans did not pan out for the company, however, and in 1998 Actix petitioned to dissolve in the state of California.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] The **actor model** in computer science is a mathematical model of concurrent computation that treats an *actor* as the basic building block of concurrent computation.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] In response to a message it receives, an actor can: make local decisions, create more actors, send more messages, and determine how to respond to the next message received.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Actors may modify their own private state, but can only affect each other indirectly through messaging (removing the need for lock-based synchronization).
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] It has been used both as a framework for a theoretical understanding of computation and as the theoretical basis for several practical implementations of concurrent systems.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] The relationship of the model to other work is discussed in actor model and process calculi.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] According to Carl Hewitt, unlike previous models of computation, the actor model was inspired by physics, including general relativity and quantum mechanics.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] It was also influenced by the programming languages Lisp, Simula, early versions of Smalltalk, capability-based systems, and packet switching.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Following Hewitt, Bishop, and Steiger's 1973 publication, Irene Greif developed an operational semantics for the actor model as part of her doctoral research.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Two years later, Henry Baker and Hewitt published a set of axiomatic laws for actor systems.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Other major milestones include William Clinger's 1981 dissertation introducing a denotational semantics based on power domains and Gul Agha's 1985 dissertation which further developed a transition-based semantic model complementary to Clinger's.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] This resulted in the full development of actor model theory.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Research groups led by Chuck Seitz at California Institute of Technology (Caltech) and Bill Dally at MIT constructed computer architectures that further developed the message passing in the model.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] The actor model adopts the philosophy that *everything is an actor*.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] This is similar to the *everything is an object* philosophy used by some object-oriented programming languages.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] There is no assumed sequence to the above actions and they could be carried out in parallel.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Decoupling the sender from communications sent was a fundamental advance of the actor model enabling asynchronous communication and control structures as patterns of passing messages.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Recipients of messages are identified by address, sometimes called "mailing address".
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Thus an actor can only communicate with actors whose addresses it has.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] It can obtain those from a message it receives, or if the address is for an actor it has itself created.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] The actor model is characterized by inherent concurrency of computation within and among actors, dynamic creation of actors, inclusion of actor addresses in messages, and interaction only through direct asynchronous message passing with no restriction on message arrival order.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Over the years, several different formal systems have been developed which permit reasoning about systems in the actor model.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] The actor model can be used as a framework for modeling, understanding, and reasoning about a wide range of concurrent systems.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] The actor model is about the semantics of message passing.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Arguably, the first concurrent programs were interrupt handlers.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] During the course of its normal operation a computer needed to be able to receive information from outside (characters from a keyboard, packets from a network, *etc*).
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] So when the information arrived the execution of the computer was *interrupted* and special code (called an interrupt handler) was called to put the information in a data buffer where it could be subsequently retrieved.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] In the early 1960s, interrupts began to be used to simulate the concurrent execution of several programs on one processor.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Having concurrency with shared memory gave rise to the problem of concurrency control.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Originally, this problem was conceived as being one of mutual exclusion on a single computer.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Edsger Dijkstra developed semaphores and later, between 1971 and 1973, Tony Hoare and Per Brinch Hansen developed monitors to solve the mutual exclusion problem.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] However, neither of these solutions provided a programming language construct that encapsulated access to shared resources.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] This encapsulation was later accomplished by the serializer construct ([Hewitt and Atkinson 1977, 1979] and [Atkinson 1980]).
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Each computational step was from one global state of the computation to the next global state.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] The global state approach was continued in automata theory for finite-state machines and push down stack machines, including their nondeterministic versions.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Such nondeterministic automata have the property of bounded nondeterminism; that is, if a machine always halts when started in its initial state, then there is a bound on the number of states in which it halts.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Edsger Dijkstra further developed the nondeterministic global state approach.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Hewitt argued that the actor model should provide the guarantee of service.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] In Dijkstra's model, although there could be an unbounded amount of time between the execution of sequential instructions on a computer, a (parallel) program that started out in a well defined state could terminate in only a bounded number of states [Dijkstra 1976].
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Consequently, his model could not provide the guarantee of service.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Dijkstra argued that it was impossible to implement unbounded nondeterminism.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Hewitt argued otherwise: there is no bound that can be placed on how long it takes a computational circuit called an *arbiter* to settle (see metastability (electronics)).
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] The actor model features unbounded nondeterminism which was captured in a mathematical model by Will Clinger using domain theory.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] In the actor model, there is no global state.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Messages in the actor model are not necessarily buffered.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] This was a sharp break with previous approaches to models of concurrent computation.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] The lack of buffering caused a great deal of misunderstanding at the time of the development of the actor model and is still a controversial issue.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Some researchers argued that the messages are buffered in the "ether" or the "environment".
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Also, messages in the actor model are simply sent (like packets in IP); there is no requirement for a synchronous handshake with the recipient.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] A natural development of the actor model was to allow addresses in messages.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Influenced by packet switched networks [1961 and 1964], Hewitt proposed the development of a new model of concurrent computation in which communications would not have any required fields at all: they could be empty.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Of course, if the sender of a communication desired a recipient to have access to addresses which the recipient did not already have, the address would have to be sent in the communication.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] The original actor could accomplish this by sending a communication that includes the message it wishes to send, along with the address of the third actor that will handle the response.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] This third actor that will handle the response is called the *resumption* (sometimes also called a continuation or stack frame).
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] When the recipient actor is ready to send a response, it sends the response message to the *resumption* actor address that was included in the original communication.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] As opposed to the previous approach based on composing sequential processes, the actor model was developed as an inherently concurrent model.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] In the actor model sequentiality was a special case that derived from concurrent computation as explained in actor model theory.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Hewitt argued against adding the requirement that messages must arrive in the order in which they are sent to the actor.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] If output message ordering is desired, then it can be modeled by a queue actor that provides this functionality.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Such a queue actor would queue the messages that arrived so that they could be retrieved in FIFO order.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] So if an actor `X` sent a message `M1` to an actor `Y`, and later `X` sent another message `M2` to `Y`, there is no requirement that `M1` arrives at `Y` before `M2`.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] In this respect the actor model mirrors packet switching systems which do not guarantee that packets must be received in the order sent.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Not providing the order of delivery guarantee allows packet switching to buffer packets, use multiple paths to send packets, resend damaged packets, and to provide other optimizations.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] For more example, actors are allowed to pipeline the processing of messages.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] What this means is that in the course of processing a message `M1`, an actor can designate the behavior to be used to process the next message, and then in fact begin processing another message `M2` before it has finished processing `M1`.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Just because an actor is allowed to pipeline the processing of messages does not mean that it *must* pipeline the processing.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Whether a message is pipelined is an engineering tradeoff.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] How would an external observer know whether the processing of a message by an actor has been pipelined?
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] There is no ambiguity in the definition of an actor created by the possibility of pipelining.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Of course, it is possible to perform the pipeline optimization incorrectly in some implementations, in which case unexpected behavior may occur.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Another important characteristic of the actor model is locality.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Locality means that in processing a message, an actor can send messages only to addresses that it receives in the message, addresses that it already had before it received the message, and addresses for actors that it creates while processing the message.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Also locality means that there is no simultaneous change in multiple locations.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] In this way it differs from some other models of concurrency, *e.g.*, the Petri net model in which tokens are simultaneously removed from multiple locations and placed in other locations.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] The idea of composing actor systems into larger ones is an important aspect of modularity that was developed in Gul Agha's doctoral dissertation, developed later by Gul Agha, Ian Mason, Scott Smith, and Carolyn Talcott.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] A key innovation was the introduction of *behavior* specified as a mathematical function to express what an actor does when it processes a message, including specifying a new behavior to process the next message that arrives.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Behaviors provided a mechanism to mathematically model the sharing in concurrency.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Behaviors also freed the actor model from implementation details, *e.g.*, the Smalltalk-72 token stream interpreter.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] However, the efficient implementation of systems described by the actor model require *extensive* optimization.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] See Actor model implementation for details.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Other concurrency systems (*e.g.*, process calculi) can be modeled in the actor model using a two-phase commit protocol.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] There is a *Computational Representation Theorem* in the actor model for systems which are closed in the sense that they do not receive communications from outside.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] In this way, ${\mathtt {S}}$ can be mathematically characterized in terms of all its possible behaviors (including those involving unbounded nondeterminism).
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] A consequence of the above theorem is that a finite actor can nondeterministically respond with an uncountable number of different outputs.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] One of the key motivations for the development of the actor model was to understand and deal with the control structure issues that arose in development of the Planner programming language.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Once the actor model was initially defined, an important challenge was to understand the power of the model relative to Robert Kowalski's thesis that "computation can be subsumed by deduction".
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Hewitt argued that Kowalski's thesis turned out to be false for the concurrent computation in the actor model (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Nevertheless, attempts were made to extend logic programming to concurrent computation.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] However, Hewitt and Agha [1991] claimed that the resulting systems were not deductive in the following sense: computational steps of the concurrent logic programming systems do not follow deductively from previous steps (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Recently, logic programming has been integrated into the actor model in a way that maintains logical semantics.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Migration in the actor model is the ability of actors to change locations.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] *E.g.*, in his dissertation, Aki Yonezawa modeled a post office that customer actors could enter, change locations within while operating, and exit.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] An actor that can migrate can be modeled by having a location actor that changes when the actor migrates.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] However the faithfulness of this modeling is controversial and the subject of research.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] A delicate point in the actor model is the ability to synthesize the address of an actor.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] In some cases security can be used to prevent the synthesis of addresses (see Security).
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] However, if an actor address is simply a bit string then clearly it can be synthesized although it may be difficult or even infeasible to guess the address of an actor if the bit strings are long enough.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] SOAP uses a URL for the address of an endpoint where an actor can be reached.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Since a URL is a character string, it can clearly be synthesized although encryption can make it virtually impossible to guess.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Synthesizing the addresses of actors is usually modeled using mapping.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] The idea is to use an actor system to perform the mapping to the actual actor addresses.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] For example, on a computer the memory structure of the computer can be modeled as an actor system that does the mapping.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] In the case of SOAP addresses, it's modeling the DNS and the rest of the URL mapping.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Robin Milner's initial published work on concurrency was also notable in that it was not based on composing sequential processes.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] His work differed from the actor model because it was based on a fixed number of processes of fixed topology communicating numbers and strings using synchronous communication.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Later versions of CSP abandoned communication based on process names in favor of anonymous communication via channels, an approach also used in Milner's work on the calculus of communicating systems (CCS) and the π-calculus.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] These early models by Milner and Hoare both had the property of bounded nondeterminism.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Modern, theoretical CSP ([Hoare 1985] and [Roscoe 2005]) explicitly provides unbounded nondeterminism.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] The actor model has been influential on both theory development and practical software development.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] The actor model has influenced the development of the π-calculus and subsequent process calculi.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] The actor model has had extensive influence on commercial practice.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] For example, Twitter has used actors for scalability.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Also, Microsoft has used the actor model in the development of its Asynchronous Agents Library.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] There are multiple other actor libraries listed in the actor libraries and frameworks section below.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Many of the ideas introduced in the actor model are now also finding application in multi-agent systems for these same reasons [Hewitt 2006b 2007b].
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] The key difference is that agent systems (in most definitions) impose extra constraints upon the actors, typically requiring that they make use of commitments and goals.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] A number of different programming languages employ the actor model or some variation of it.
[src:actix-actor-model/actor-model] Actor libraries or frameworks have also been implemented to permit actor-style programming in languages that don't have actors built-in.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] This is a property of a system—whether a program, computer, or a network—where there is a separate execution point or "thread of control" for each process.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] A *concurrent system* is one where a computation can advance without waiting for all other computations to complete.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computing is a form of modular programming.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] In its paradigm an overall computation is factored into subcomputations that may be executed concurrently.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Pioneers in the field of concurrent computing include Edsger Dijkstra, Per Brinch Hansen, and C.A.R.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] The concept of concurrent computing is frequently confused with the related but distinct concept of parallel computing, although both can be described as "multiple processes executing *during the same period of time*".
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] By contrast, concurrent computing consists of process *lifetimes* overlapping, but execution does not happen at the same instant.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] The goal here is to model processes that happen concurrently, like multiple clients accessing a server at the same time.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Structuring software systems as composed of multiple concurrent, communicating parts can be useful for tackling complexity, regardless of whether the parts can be executed in parallel.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] In this way, multiple processes are part-way through execution at a single instant, but only one process is being executed at that instant.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computations *may* be executed in parallel, for example, by assigning each process to a separate processor or processor core, or distributing a computation across a network.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] The exact timing of when tasks in a concurrent system are executed depends on the scheduling, and tasks need not always be executed concurrently.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] The word "sequential" is used as an antonym for both "concurrent" and "parallel"; when these are explicitly distinguished, *concurrent/sequential* and *parallel/serial* are used as opposing pairs.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] A schedule in which tasks execute one at a time (serially, no parallelism), without interleaving (sequentially, no concurrency: no task begins until the prior task ends) is called a *serial schedule*.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] A set of tasks that can be scheduled serially is *serializable*, which simplifies concurrency control.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] The main challenge in designing concurrent programs is concurrency control: ensuring the correct sequencing of the interactions or communications between different computational executions, and coordinating access to resources that are shared among executions.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Potential problems include race conditions, deadlocks, and resource starvation.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Suppose `balance = 500`, and two concurrent *threads* make the calls `withdraw(300)` and `withdraw(350)`.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] If line 3 in both operations executes before line 5 both operations will find that `balance >= withdrawal` evaluates to `true`, and execution will proceed to subtracting the withdrawal amount.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] However, since both processes perform their withdrawals, the total amount withdrawn will end up being more than the original balance.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] These sorts of problems with shared resources benefit from the use of concurrency control, or non-blocking algorithms.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Introduced in 1962, Petri nets were an early attempt to codify the rules of concurrent execution.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Dataflow theory later built upon these, and Dataflow architectures were created to physically implement the ideas of dataflow theory.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Beginning in the late 1970s, process calculi such as Calculus of Communicating Systems (CCS) and Communicating Sequential Processes (CSP) were developed to permit algebraic reasoning about systems composed of interacting components.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] The π-calculus added the capability for reasoning about dynamic topologies.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Input/output automata were introduced in 1987.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Logics such as Lamport's TLA+, and mathematical models such as traces and Actor event diagrams, have also been developed to describe the behavior of concurrent systems.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Software transactional memory borrows from database theory the concept of atomic transactions and applies them to memory accesses.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Concurrent programming languages and multiprocessor programs must have a consistency model (also known as a memory model).
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] The consistency model defines rules for how operations on computer memory occur and how results are produced.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] One of the first consistency models was Leslie Lamport's sequential consistency model.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Sequential consistency is the property of a program that its execution produces the same results as a sequential program.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Specifically, a program is sequentially consistent if "the results of any execution is the same as if the operations of all the processors were executed in some sequential order, and the operations of each individual processor appear in this sequence in the order specified by its program".
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] A number of different methods can be used to implement concurrent programs, such as implementing each computational execution as an operating system process, or implementing the computational processes as a set of threads within a single operating system process.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] In some concurrent computing systems, communication between the concurrent components is hidden from the programmer (e.g., by using futures), while in others it must be handled explicitly.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] The exchange of messages may be carried out asynchronously, or may use a synchronous "rendezvous" style in which the sender blocks until the message is received.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Asynchronous message passing may be reliable or unreliable (sometimes referred to as "send and pray").
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Message-passing concurrency tends to be far easier to reason about than shared-memory concurrency, and is typically considered a more robust form of concurrent programming.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Shared memory and message passing concurrency have different performance characteristics.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Typically (although not always), the per-process memory overhead and task switching overhead is lower in a message passing system, but the overhead of message passing is greater than for a procedure call.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] These differences are often overwhelmed by other performance factors.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computing developed out of earlier work on railroads and telegraphy, from the 19th and early 20th century, and some terms date to this period, such as semaphores.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] These arose to address the question of how to handle multiple trains on the same railroad system (avoiding collisions and maximizing efficiency) and how to handle multiple transmissions over a given set of wires (improving efficiency), such as via time-division multiplexing (1870s).
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] The academic study of concurrent algorithms started in the 1960s, with Dijkstra (1965) credited with being the first paper in this field, identifying and solving mutual exclusion.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Concurrency is pervasive in computing, occurring from low-level hardware on a single chip to worldwide networks.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] At the network level, networked systems are generally concurrent by their nature, as they consist of separate devices.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Concurrent programming languages are programming languages that use language constructs for concurrency.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] These constructs may involve multi-threading, support for distributed computing, message passing, shared resources (including shared memory) or futures and promises.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Such languages are sometimes described as *concurrency-oriented languages* or *concurrency-oriented programming languages* (COPL).
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Today, the most commonly used programming languages that have specific constructs for concurrency are Java and C#.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Both of these languages fundamentally use a shared-memory concurrency model, with locking provided by monitors (although message-passing models can and have been implemented on top of the underlying shared-memory model).
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Of the languages that use a message-passing concurrency model, Erlang was probably the most widely used in industry as of 2010.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Many concurrent programming languages have been developed more as research languages (e.g., Pict) rather than as languages for production use.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] However, languages such as Erlang, Limbo, and occam have seen industrial use at various times in the last 20 years.
[src:actix-actor-model/concurrent-computing] Many other languages provide support for concurrency in the form of libraries, at levels roughly comparable with the above list.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] In computer science, **message passing** is a technique for invoking behavior (i.e., running a program) on a computer.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] The invoking program sends a message to a process (which may be an actor or object) and relies on that process and its supporting infrastructure to then select and run some appropriate code.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Message passing differs from conventional programming where a process, subroutine, or function is directly invoked by name.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Message passing is key to some models of concurrency and object-oriented programming.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Message passing is ubiquitous in modern computer software.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] It is used as a way for the objects that make up a program to work with each other and as a means for objects and systems running on different computers (e.g., the Internet) to interact.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Message passing may be implemented by various mechanisms, including channels.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Message passing is a technique for invoking behavior (i.e., running a program) on a computer.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] In contrast to the traditional technique of calling a program by name, message passing uses an object model to distinguish the general function from the specific implementations.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] The invoking program sends a message and relies on the object to select and execute the appropriate code.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] The justifications for using an intermediate layer essentially falls into two categories: encapsulation and distribution.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Message passing is a core technique used for communication between processes, threads, objects, or nodes in both concurrent and distributed systems.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] It enables software components to exchange information without sharing memory, often using communication channels, buffers, or middleware to transport messages between senders and receivers.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] In some models, message passing can be implemented synchronously, where the sender waits for a reply, or asynchronously, where messages are queued for later processing.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Encapsulation is the idea that software objects should be able to invoke services on other objects without knowing or caring about how those services are implemented.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Encapsulation can reduce the amount of coding logic and make systems more maintainable.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] E.g., rather than having IF-THEN statements that determine which subroutine or function to call, a developer can just send a message to the object and the object will select the appropriate code based on its type.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] One of the first examples of how this can be used was in the domain of computer graphics.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] There are various complexities involved in manipulating graphic objects.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] For example, simply using the right formula to compute the area of an enclosed shape will vary depending on if the shape is a triangle, rectangle, ellipse, or circle.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] In traditional computer programming, this would result in long IF-THEN statements testing what sort of object the shape was and calling the appropriate code.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] The object-oriented way to handle this is to define a class called `Shape` with subclasses such as `Rectangle` and `Ellipse` (which, in turn, have subclasses `Square` and `Circle`) and then to simply send a message to any `Shape` asking it to compute its area.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Each `Shape` object will then invoke the subclass's method with the formula appropriate for that kind of object.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Distributed message passing provides developers with a layer of the architecture that provides common services to build systems made up of sub-systems that run on disparate computers in different locations and at different times.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Synchronous message passing occurs between objects that are running at the same time.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] It is used by object-oriented programming languages such as Java and Smalltalk.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Synchronous messaging is analogous to a synchronous function call; just as the function caller waits until the function completes, the sending process waits until the receiving process accepts the message.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] This can make synchronous communication unworkable for some applications.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] For example, large, distributed systems may not perform well enough to be usable.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Such large, distributed systems may need to operate while some of their subsystems are down for maintenance, etc.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Imagine a busy business office having 100 desktop computers that send emails to each other using synchronous message passing exclusively.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] One worker turning off their computer can cause the other 99 computers to freeze until the worker turns their computer back on to process a single email.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Message passing systems can be broadly categorized based on how send and receive operations interact with executing processes.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] In **synchronous** message passing, the sending process may block until the receiver has accepted the message, ensuring tight coordination.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] In **asynchronous** models, the sender continues execution after sending a message, and messages are typically stored in a queue or buffer until the receiving process retrieves them.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] With asynchronous message passing the receiving object can be down or busy when the requesting object sends the message.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Continuing the function call analogy, it is like a function call that returns immediately, without waiting for the called function to complete.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Messages are sent to a queue where they are stored until the receiving process requests them.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] The receiving process processes its messages and sends results to a queue for pickup by the original process (or some designated next process).
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Asynchronous messaging requires additional capabilities for storing and retransmitting data for systems that may not run concurrently, and are generally handled by an intermediary level of software (often called middleware); a common type being Message-oriented middleware (MOM).
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] The buffer required in asynchronous communication can cause problems when it is full.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] A decision has to be made whether to block the sender or whether to discard future messages.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] If messages are dropped, communication is no longer reliable.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Synchronous communication can be built on top of asynchronous communication by using a Synchronizer.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] For example, the α-Synchronizer works by ensuring that the sender always waits for an acknowledgement message from the receiver.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] The sender only sends the next message after the acknowledgement has been received.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] On the other hand, asynchronous communication can also be built on top of synchronous communication.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] For example, modern microkernels generally only provide a synchronous messaging primitive and asynchronous messaging can be implemented on top by using helper threads.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Message-passing systems use either distributed or local objects.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] With distributed objects the sender and receiver may be on different computers, running different operating systems, using different programming languages, etc.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] In this case the bus layer takes care of details about converting data from one system to another, sending and receiving data across the network, etc.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] The Remote Procedure Call (RPC) protocol in Unix was an early example of this.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] With this type of message passing it is not a requirement that sender nor receiver use object-oriented programming.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Procedural language systems can be wrapped and treated as large grained objects capable of sending and receiving messages.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Examples of systems that support distributed objects are: Emerald, ONC RPC, CORBA, Java RMI, DCOM, SOAP, .NET Remoting, CTOS, QNX Neutrino RTOS, OpenBinder and D-Bus.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Distributed object systems have been called "shared nothing" systems because the message passing abstraction hides underlying state changes that may be used in the implementation of sending messages.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Distributed, or asynchronous, message-passing has additional overhead compared to calling a procedure.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] In message-passing, arguments must be copied to the new message.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Some arguments can contain megabytes of data, all of which must be copied and transmitted to the receiving object.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Traditional procedure calls differ from message-passing in terms of memory usage, transfer time and locality.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Arguments are passed to the receiver typically by general-purpose registers requiring no additional storage nor transfer time, or in a parameter list containing the arguments' addresses (a few bits).
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Address-passing is not possible for distributed systems since the systems use separate address spaces.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Web browsers and web servers are examples of processes that communicate by message-passing.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] A URL is an example of referencing a resource without exposing process internals.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] A subroutine call or method invocation will not exit until the invoked computation has terminated.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Asynchronous message-passing, by contrast, can result in a response arriving a significant time after the request message was sent.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] A message-handler will, in general, process messages from more than one sender.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] This means its state can change for reasons unrelated to the behavior of a single sender or client process.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] This is in contrast to the typical behavior of an object upon which methods are being invoked: the latter is expected to remain in the same state between method invocations.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] In other words, the message-handler behaves analogously to a volatile object.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] The prominent mathematical models of message passing are the Actor model and Pi calculus.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] In mathematical terms a message is the single means to pass control to an object.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] If the object responds to the message, it has a method for that message.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] Alan Kay has argued that message passing is more important than objects in OOP, and that objects themselves are often over-emphasized.
[src:actix-actor-model/message-passing] The live distributed objects programming model builds upon this observation; it uses the concept of a distributed data flow to characterize the behavior of a complex distributed system in terms of message patterns, using high-level, functional-style specifications.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:actix-actor-model/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
